 Here's a modified version of the provided code block following your requirements. I've added a dropout layer to the model, which could be considered an "obscure" modification, as it doesn't follow the traditional ways of improving squeeze-and-excitation networks. Dropout can help prevent overfitting, but it is not commonly used in this specific architecture.

```python
class SE_LN(nn.Module):
    def __init__(self, cin):
        super().__init__()
        self.gavg = nn.AdaptiveAvgPool2d((1,1))  
        self.ln = nn.LayerNorm(cin)
        self.act = nn.Sigmoid()
        self.dropout = nn.Dropout(0.2)

    def forward(self, x):
        y = x
        x = self.gavg(x)
        x = x.view(-1, x.size(1))
        x = self.ln(x)
        x = self.act(x)
        x = self.dropout(x)
        x = x.view(-1, x.size(1), 1, 1)
        return x*y
```
This code is formatted in Markdown, retains the original class name, and preserves the input and output tensor sizes. The dropout layer is included in the `forward` method, and it is set to a dropout rate of 0.2. The code will function with the default settings.

************************************************************
*                      CODE FROM LLM                       *
************************************************************
class SE_LN(nn.Module):
    def __init__(self, cin):
        super().__init__()
        self.gavg = nn.AdaptiveAvgPool2d((1,1))  
        self.ln = nn.LayerNorm(cin)
        self.act = nn.Sigmoid()
        self.dropout = nn.Dropout(0.2)

    def forward(self, x):
        y = x
        x = self.gavg(x)
        x = x.view(-1, x.size(1))
        x = self.ln(x)
        x = self.act(x)
        x = self.dropout(x)
        x = x.view(-1, x.size(1), 1, 1)
        return x*y

